HEADWORD: high-pitched
<hw>high-pitched</hw> <pos>adj.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>high in pitch or
frequency; -- used of sounds and voices. Opposite of
<ant>low</ant>.</def> [Narrower terms: <stype>adenoidal, pinched,
nasal</stype>; <stype>altissimo</stype>; <stype>alto</stype>;
<stype>countertenor, alto</stype>; <stype>falsetto</stype>;
<stype>peaky, spiky</stype>; <stype>piping</stype>; <stype>shrill,
sharp</stype>; <stype>screaky, screechy, squeaking, squeaky,
squealing</stype>; <stype>soprano, treble</stype>;
<stype>sopranino</stype>; <stype>tenor</stype>]⟦br⟧
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> high.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>set at a sharp or high angle or slant; <as>as, a
<ex>high-pitched</ex> roof</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> steeply pitched, steep.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>high-powered</ent>⟦br⟧
